==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: electron-volt
<hw>electron-volt</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a unit of energy, being equal
to the kinetic energy acquired by an electron when accelerated through a
potential difference of one volt. It is equal to 1.602 x
10<exp>-19</exp> Joules. It is abbreviated <abbr>eV</abbr>.</def>
<note>The unit electron-volt is often used to express the rest mass and
the energy of fundamental particles, especially when accelerated to high
velocity in an accelerator. In accelerators, the units encountered are
more commonly megaelectron-volts (MeV or million electron-volts) and
giga-electron-volts (GeV or billion electron-volts).</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

